05783nam a22009975i 9780814786475DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20062006nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808147864757 a10.18574/97808147864752doi  a(DE-B1597)548222  a(OCoLC)319491929  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aKF510b.M37 2006 7aLAW0380302bisacsh04a306.810100aMarriage Proposals :bQuestioning a Legal Status /ced. by Anita Bernstein. 1aNew York, NY : bNew York University Press, c[2006] 4c©2006  a1 online resource  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tPart I. Challenges to the Status of Marriage -- tChapter 1. The Meaning of Marriage -- tChapter 2. Taking Government Out of the Marriage Business -- tChapter 3. What Place for Marriage (E)quality in Marriage Promotion? -- tPart II. Some Perils of Attempting Abolition -- tChapter 4. Anthropological Perspectives on the Abolition of Marriage -- tChapter 5. Marriage as a “Badge and Incident” of Democratic Freedom -- tChapter 6. The State of Marriage and the State in Marriage -- tAfterword -- tAbout the Contributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe essays in Marriage Proposals envision a variety of scenarios in which adults would continue to join themselves together seeking permanent companionship and sustenance, linking sexual intimacy to a long commitment, usually caring for each other, and building new families. What would disappear are the legal consequences associated with marriage. No joint income tax return; no immigration privileges like the “fiancée visa” or the right to bring in a husband or wife; no special statuses for prison visits or hospital decisions; no prerogative to remain silent in court by claiming “confidential marital communications”; no pension entitlements; no marital benefits and detriments regarding criminal or civil liability.The anthology makes a unique contribution amid the two marriage furors of the day: same-sex marriage and the Bush Administration's “marriage movement” (that marrying is good and more marriages would be better for society). Abolishing the legal category of marriage is the only policy suggestion in current American discourse that speaks to both causes. Activists on both sides of the same-sex marriage fight, along with marriage movement partisans, all seek improvement through law reform. Marriage Proposals gives them a viable reform—abolition of marriage as a legal status—for fighting battles in the courtroom and the streets.Contributors include Anita Bernstein, Peggy Cooper Davis, Martha Albertson Fineman, Linda C. McClain, Marshall Miller, Lawrence Rosen, Mary Lyndon Shanley, and Dorian Solot.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aMarriage lawxPhilosophy. 0aMarriage lawzUnited StatesxPhilosophy. 7aLAW / Family Law / Marriage.2bisacsh  aAdministrations.  aBush.  aamid.  aanthology.  acontribution.  aday.  afurors.  aimprovement.  amakes.  amarriage.  amovement.  areform.  asame-sex.  aseeking.  athat.  athrough.  aunique.1 aBernstein, Anita, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBernstein, Anita, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aDavis, Peggy Cooper, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFineman, Martha Albertson, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMcClain, Linda C., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMiller, Marshall, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aRosen, Lawrence, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aS